{%- comment -%}
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
PRE-ORDER CHECK (custom vcollect)
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Outputs the string "true" when a product can be pre-ordered, and nothing otherwise.

Pre-order is the intersection of three conditions:
  1. the official release date is still in the future (vcollect.date_sortie)
  2. at least one variant can be bought
  3. the merchant opened pre-orders on that product (vcollect.precommande)

Condition 3 is what lets the same unreleased product be handled two ways. With pre-orders open, stock is sold right
away and shipped on release day. With pre-orders closed, stock can sit in the warehouse while the page keeps
collecting emails (see 'waitlist-form'), which is what a merchant wants when the allocation is not confirmed yet.

An unset vcollect.precommande reads as "closed" on purpose. The safe default is the one that cannot take money for a
product nobody promised to ship: opening a pre-order has to be a deliberate act, never a side effect of receiving
stock.

Built on top of 'coming-soon-check' rather than repeating the date comparison, so the release date keeps a single
source of truth. Tests product.available, which is true as soon as ONE variant is buyable: testing the selected
variant would drop a product out of pre-order just because the shopper is looking at a sold-out size.

Usage:
  {%- capture is_pre_order -%}{%- render 'pre-order-check', product: product -%}{%- endcapture -%}
  {%- assign is_pre_order = is_pre_order | strip -%}

********************************************
Supported variables
********************************************

* product: the product to test
{%- endcomment -%}

{%- capture is_coming_soon -%}{%- render 'coming-soon-check', product: product -%}{%- endcapture -%}
{%- assign is_coming_soon = is_coming_soon | strip -%}

{%- comment -%}
Compared against true AND against 'true' because a boolean metafield reads back as a real boolean in Liquid while the
same value read through other paths is a string. Testing `== blank` instead would be wrong twice over: in Liquid,
false and nil are both blank, so an explicitly closed pre-order and an unset one would be indistinguishable from an
empty string, and the test would silently pass on a value of false.
{%- endcomment -%}
{%- assign pre_order_opened = false -%}
{%- if product.metafields.vcollect.precommande.value == true or product.metafields.vcollect.precommande.value == 'true' -%}
  {%- assign pre_order_opened = true -%}
{%- endif -%}

{%- if is_coming_soon == 'true' and product.available and pre_order_opened -%}
  {{- 'true' -}}
{%- endif -%}
